full_text(utf-8): b"I NEEDED my mom home. The workplace my father so often invaded, with me in tow, with his demands to be on a floor where he didn't belong so he could be treated like my mother's only patient...her colleagues understood. Higher-ups did not. I revere nurses. And the fact we're-"

full_text: When my dad died, every one of those nurses chipped in their PTO to make sure my mom could stay home and take care of me, paid, until all the paperwork went through for us to get government checks. They're my heroes. I was 10&11 years old, waking up through the night in tears.
full_text(utf-8): b"When my dad died, every one of those nurses chipped in their PTO to make sure my mom could stay home and take care of me, paid, until all the paperwork went through for us to get government checks. They're my heroes. I was 10&11 years old, waking up through the night in tears."

full_text: This is still one of the things I am absolutely proudest of my mom for, but it's also something no one should've ever had to do. What would've happened if another nurse needed extensive invasive surgery after that & was not only out of PTO but no one else had PTO left to donate?
